[[Image:West End Adult Evening School ca1890s Boston byAHFolsom BPL.png|400px|thumb|right|[[West End, Boston|West End]] Adult Evening School, Boston, ca.1890s; photo by A.H. Folsom (Boston Public Library)]]

'''Augustine H. Folsom''' (died 1926) or '''A.H. Folsom''' was a photographer in the [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]-area in the late 19th and early 20th-centuries.<ref>Boston Directory. 1873.</ref><ref>Boston Almanac. 1888</ref> Subjects included buildings in Massachusetts, Maine, and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].  Folsom lived in [[Roxbury, Boston|Roxbury]], ca.1870-1926.<ref>Boston Landmarks Commission. 1984 Survey and planning grant, part 1 - Parker Hill / Mission Hill project completion report. 1985</ref> Folsom showed photographic work in the [[Massachusetts Charitable Mechanic Association]] exhibitions of 1874 and 1881.<ref>Catalogue of articles on display ... Faneuil and Quincy Halls, of the twelfth exhibition of the Massachusetts Charitable Mechanic Association, Boston, September and October, 1874. Boston: Rand, Avery, and Co., printers, 1874. [http://books.google.com/books?id=_AwAAAAAMAAJ Google books]</ref><ref>Photographic Times, Jan. 1875. [http://books.google.com/books?id=VxwXAAAAYAAJ Google books]</ref><ref>Mechanic Association : fourteenth triennial exhibition. Open September and October. Huntington Ave. and West Newton St. Boston. Boston: Rand, Avery, 1881</ref>

Works by Folsom reside in the collections of the Boston Public Library; Historic New England; Metropolitan Museum, NY;<ref>http://www.metmuseum.org/Works_of_Art/collection_database/photographs/construction_of_south_street_station_boston_massachusetts_augustine_h_folsom//objectview.aspx?OID=190015734&collID=19&dd1=19</ref> Museum of Fine Arts, Boston;<ref>http://www.mfa.org/collections/search_art.asp?recview=true&id=373482</ref> the Georgia State Archives;<ref>http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/vang/id:pck244-85</ref><ref>http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/vang/id:pck272-85</ref> and the American Antiquarian Society.<ref>http://www.americanantiquarian.org/Exhibitions/Womanswork/artists.htm</ref>

